# Accessibility

## 1. Applies when
Always. Accessibility is a baseline requirement, not an optional feature.

## 2. This document owns
Accessibility design principles and compliance targets.
Visual accessibility: colorblind modes, high-contrast, text scaling.
Auditory accessibility: subtitles, closed captions, audio cues visualization.
Motor accessibility: input remapping, toggle vs. hold, assist modes.
Cognitive accessibility: difficulty options, tutorial design, UI clarity.
Accessibility testing and player feedback integration.
Platform-specific accessibility requirements (Xbox, PlayStation, etc.).

## 3. This document does NOT own
UI layout specifics (→ UI_UX_Design, but coordinates closely).
Tutorial content and scripting (→ Narrative_Pipeline or Mission_Design).
Input system implementation (→ Gameplay_Systems or Technical_Design).
Localization and translation (→ Localization).

## 4. Recommended chapter structure
1. Accessibility Principles & Compliance · 2. Visual Accessibility ·
3. Auditory Accessibility · 4. Motor Accessibility · 5. Cognitive Accessibility ·
6. Testing & Player Feedback · 7. Platform Requirements

## 5. Common boundaries
- Accessibility owns "what accommodations exist"; UI_UX_Design owns "how they're presented".
- Subtitles specifications belong here; dialogue text belongs to Narrative_Script.
- Input remapping belongs here; input action design belongs to Gameplay_Systems.

## 6. Common audit rules
- Check that accessibility requirements are referenced in UI_UX_Design.
- Check that subtitle/caption specs reference Narrative_Script.
